<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-03-28T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-03-28T18:00:00-05:00" n="618" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d618">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/17680a</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                Special Representative <persName type="to">Rodgers</persName>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-03-28T18:00:00-05:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 28, 1916, 6 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>11. Approach <hi rend="italic">de facto</hi> Government and tactfully
                            suggest that, pending settlement of terms of protocol, Government
                            consent to our forces using railroad for purpose of bringing up
                            supplies. Point out that this Government freely granted right to General
                            Carranza <pb facs="0580" n="504" xml:id="pg_504"/> to use our railroads
                            at a time when it was vitally important for him not only for supplies
                            but for troops, also point out that by depriving this Government of use
                            of railroads it is making more difficult the operations of troops and
                            will consequently necessitate their presence for a longer time in
                            Mexico.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>